Hi JGOH,

That's awesome. Have you ever tried the exact steps as below?

git clone https://github.com/PerfectlySoft/PerfectTemplate.git
swift build

if success, then add this dependency to Package.swift:

.Package(url: "https://github.com/PerfectlySoft/Perfect-CURL.git", majorVersion:2, minor: 0)

Then please try the swift build again without Xcode:
swift build

If success, then please try add the PostgreSQL to the Package.swift as:
.Package(url: "https://github.com/PerfectlySoft/Perfect-PostgreSQL.git", majorVersion:2, minor: 0)

Before compiling, however, please make sure libpq-dev has been installed. If not, please try:
brew install libpqxx

Then finally try:
swift build
swift package generate-xcodeproj
open ./PerfectTemplate.xcodeproj/

Wish you could see the PerfectlyTemplate back to Xcode then.

– Rockford Wei

Hi JGOH,

Thank you for providing this important information. Unfortunately, this issue has been confirmed as the swift bug itself. Perfect community contributes a few unofficial solutions before the swift.org solves it.

1. If the Xcode command tools are useless to you, please try uninstalling them.

2. If the command tools are still useful to some of your projects, then please try an alternative approach, i.e., block the pkgconfig from the default path by export PKG_CONFIG_PATH= to somewhere else, as below:

Here's a messy workaround for getting Perfect-CURL to compile with both pkg-config and the developer tools installed. This prevents pkg-config from adding /usr/include to the header search path, allowing the compiler to use the headers in the SDK and avoiding https://bugs.swift.org/browse/SR-1567.

(1) copy `/usr/local/Homebrew/Library/Homebrew/os/mac/pkgconfig/10.12/libcurl.pc` to the project directory

(2) change its "prefix" value to: `/Applications/Xcode.app/Contents/Developer/Platforms/MacOSX.platform/Developer/SDKs/MacOSX.sdk/usr`

(3). build the project with `PKG_CONFIG_PATH=$PWD swift build`

(4). generate the Xcode project with `PKG_CONFIG_PATH=$PWD swift package generate-xcodeproj`

If you don't mind, I would like to close this issue because there is a duplicated but more concise issue raised as ISS-316. You can follow this new one until fully resolved.

Thank you & Good luck.
